properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Periods of snow are forecast to begin this evening. Snow will become heavy at times early Tuesday morning. The snow will combine with strong northerly winds gusting to 70 km/h to cause reduced visibilities in blowing snow overnight tonight and Tuesday. Conditions along the coast are expected to improve Tuesday afternoon as temperatures rise. Snowfall amounts of 20 cm are expected by Tuesday evening, with higher amounts likely inland and over higher terrain. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

However, northernmost regions may see an improvement as early as Tuesday night. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 20 cm is expected. A low pressure system near the Great Lakes will track southeastward to lie south of Nova Scotia by Tuesday morning. Snow ahead of this system will spread slowly eastward across the province today, reaching northern regions this evening. Over southwestern Nova Scotia, the snow will change over to ice pellets or freezing rain near midnight, then taper off Tuesday morning. For Halifax, the Valley, and south shore areas, precipitation will remain as snow throughout the event but may become mixed with ice pellets before morning on Tuesday. Total snowfall amounts near 15 cm are expected by Tuesday morning. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
